text.tspan: 6.7MAINTAIN VESSEL'S CLASS/ SEAWORTHINESS ETCThe Technical Superintendent ensures that all trading certificates of the vessels remain valid at all times; copies of all the certificatesare maintained in Phoenix and he coordinates with the master well before expiry of any certificate for arranging a Classificationsurveyor to have same revalidated. As and when new certificates are received by Company, the Technical Superintendent shallforward the same to the vessel and retains a copy in the office.The Technical Superintendent shall be responsible for ensuring that all surveys whether statutory or continuous cycle are carried outand credited prior to their due dates. At the same time it shall be ensured by the Technical Superintendent that the Masters and ChiefEngineer of the vessels are updated with the latest copies of the Class Quarterly and Annual survey status report to assist them inplanning out the surveys.Prior to the due dates, the Master shall indicate to the office a list of items he proposes to present for survey along with the port ofsurvey. The Technical Superintendent at that time shall verify from the survey status report of the Classification whether all items dueare being presented or if any other item which is scheduled to fall due in the near future can be clubbed together with an intention ofreducing the cost towards surveyor’s visit.The Master shall thereafter be advised accordingly to make necessary arrangement for Surveyor’s attendance through the agents.On completion of any survey, a copy of the certificate and / or survey report shall be forwarded to the office.The certificate / survey status in PHOENIX shall be maintained for each vessel by the Master and concerned TechnicalSuperintendent and updated as and when required. If a recommendation is issued by the surveyor, necessary corrective actions shall be taken to have same deleted prior its due date.Any contract for repair/maintenance of vessel equipment is made by the Technical Department in consultation with the GeneralManager. Where the contract affects the fleet the Managing Director is also consulted.6.8VERIFICATION OF REPAIR WORKThe Master and the Chief Engineer will sign contractor’s repair sheets for jobs done on board. If a Technical Superintendent is alsoattending the repairs then it is endorsed by him. However the Technical Department is responsible for arranging the repairs andapproving the invoices.6.9MAINTAIN DISCIPLINE & OPERATIONAL EFFICIENCYThe Technical Department deals with the vessel on a day to day basis for maintaining discipline and optimum operational efficiency. 6.10SUPERINTENDENT HANDOVER6.10.1SUPERINTENDENTCompany has a system of back-up superintendent, who shall keep abreast with happenings of the other vessels on a daily basis.When the superintendent responsible for these vessels is on travel, absent due to sickness or proceeding on holiday – he can provideefficient supervision/ advice to the ships. In case of back-up superintendent’s absence at the same time, the General Manager shallprovide the supervision/ advice to the concerned ships. When a Superintendent expects to be away from duty for more than 7 days and not able to be contacted during this time, a TravelMemo Form TA 14 shall be prepared and submitted to the General Manager. If the duration is expected to be 7 days or less, a memoor message is to be prepared and circulated which covers the following for each vessel:1. Vessel Namea) Any open issue related to equipment not functioning properly or requiring follow up in terms of support.Main EngineAux EnginePurifiers.Main Air Compressors.Cargo Equipment.Any other equipmentb) Vessel next port of call with ETA.c) Logistics and supplies to be made in the next port.d) Surveys or servicing to be arranged in the next port.e) Requisitions requiring approval.f) Closure of any deficiency or COC.6.10.2CHANGE OF VESSEL’S SUPERINTENDENT OR HIGHER RANKIn case of change of vessel’s superintendent, either due to his promotion or resignation, the outgoing superintendent shall preparedetailed handing over notes for his successor. The handover notes should be comprehensive and should include comments on all therelevant issues on equipment, machinery, procedures, etc. concerning vessels he is responsible for. It is required that the handovernotes are prepared and written to a high standard – both in terms of written English and technical/ professional competence. It shallbe discussed with the General Manager for completeness and revised as necessary. The outgoing superintendent shall familiarize theincoming superintendent as necessary.
